빠르게 linear regression 을 훑고. GLM 을 중심으로 살펴본다.
많은 경우에 있어서 종속변수가 정규분포되어 있다는 가정을 할 수 없는 경우도 있으며 범주형 변수가 종속변수인 경우도 있다.
따라서, 서비스단에서의 대부분의 선택은 GLM 이다.
GLM 으로 일정수준이상의 prediction 을 해낼수 있으면 땡큐다. 모델적용이 훨 수월해진다.

linear regression

  • dependent variable : the value to be predicted
  • indepndent variable : the predictors

  • Single linear regression : a single independent var.
  • Multiple linear regression : two or more independent var.
Ordinary Least Squares Estimation
  • In order to determine the optimal estimates of α and β,
  • an estimation method known as Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) was used
  • error : the difference between the actual y value and the predicted y value 
head(faithful)
# 위의 산식에 의해 직접 simple linear regression 을 계산해본다. 
b <- stats::cov(waiting, eruptions) / stats::var(waiting)
a <- mean(eruptions) - b * mean(waiting)
plot(waiting, eruptions)
abline(a = a, b = b, col = "blue") 

# 기본 lm function 의 결과와 비교.
model <- lm(eruptions ~ waiting, data = faithful)
plot(faithful$waiting, faithful$eruptions)
abline(model, col = "red")
abline(a = 0, b = cor(faithful$waiting, faithful$eruptions), col = "violet")

print(paste("a : " , a , " model's intercept : ", model$coefficients[[1]]))
print(paste("b : " , b , " model's weight of wating : ", model$coefficients[[2]]))
Correlation
  • The correlation between two variables is a number that indicates how closely their relationship follows a straight line
  • weak 0.1 ~ 0.3 / moderate 0.3 ~ 0.5 / string 0.5 ~ 
calcuated_cor <- stats::cov(faithful$waiting, faithful$eruptions) / (stats::sd(faithful$eruptions) * stats::sd(faithful$waiting))
method_cor    <- cor(faithful$eruptions, faithful$waiting)
print(paste(calcuated_cor, method_cor, sep = " "))
[1] "0.900811168321813 0.900811168321813"
sf <- as.data.frame(scale(faithful, center = F))
sm <- lm(sf$eruptions ~ sf$waiting)
plot(sf$waiting, sf$eruptions, xlim = c(0, 1.5), ylim = c(0,1.5))
abline(sm, col = "red")
abline(a = 0, b = method_cor, col = "blue")

multiple linear regression

  • The goal is now to solve for β,
  • the vector of regression coef cients that minimizes the sum of the squared errors between the predicted and actual Y values. 
reg <- function(y, x) {
  x <- as.matrix(x)
  x <- cbind(Intercept = 1, x)
  b <- solve(t(x) %*% x) %*% t(x) %*% y
  colnames(b) <- "estimate"
  print(b)
}
reg(mtcars$mpg, mtcars[2:3])

cyl       -1.58727681
disp      -0.02058363
